\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quality of Consumption in the developing countries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demand studies in the developing world often work with data that is much
 sparser and has overall less details on the individual households.
 Current surveys mitigate many such issues - but the problems that arise
 out of non-uniform institutions themselves make the standardisation of
 data across the developing countries rather challenging.
 Studies of consumption of quality in the developing countries have therefore
 often limited themselves to food where the measurement of quality is independen
t of consumed brand or type - details that are often not recorded in a typical
 consumer survey.
 Since a significant chunk of income is spent on food for most of the population
 in the developing countries, the variation in quality in food gives us
 a good picture of quality substitution.
 Still, problems like segmentation of price - due the lack of a cheap transport
 infrastructure and a large enough firm size - makes the analysis of quality
 particularly prone to error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the current study, we attempt to quantify the choice of quality in the
 developing world.
 Instead of focusing on food quality alone, we also observe the effect of
 vast differences in life-style that living in urban vs rural areas would
 bring to the consumer in a developing country.
 The sheer lack of availability of certain goods in the rural areas - we
 believe - should also be noted in the consumption of quality.
 We comment on how overall quality may vary with economic inequalities across
 multiple economies as the consumer spreads the expenditure on quality across
 the commodity groups (food, energy etc.).
 This may provide us a better understanding of how quality of consumption
 changes in response to vast economic changes such as urban developments
 or market centralisation.
 This could be of interest both from a general demand analysis perspective
 and from a more specific conspicuous consumption perspective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To observe quality of consumption with respect to income inequalities across
 the developing countries, we motivate a model for substitution between
 a consumer's long-term needs that are fulfilled with ownership of assets
 or improvement of the socio-economic standing and the consumer's short-term
 needs that are fulfilled with improved quality of consumption.
 The socio-economic standing of the consumer is determined by an order of
 what we identify as the parameters for status (income, education, occupation)
 as well as a history of quality of consumption.
 These parameters do not all have the same effect on the long-term socio-economi
c standing of the consumer.
 The improvement in quality of expenditure is measured with the expensive
 non-durable consumption (ENDC).
 We surmise that the distribution of quality across the consumption groups
 (food, energy, housing etc.) should be affected by the long-term needs of
 (asset accumulation, educational needs etc.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth emphasising that we differentiate between quality consumption
 and conspicuous consumption.
 At least semantically speaking, the term conspicuous consumption encompasses
 only the exclusive consumption by the rich.
 In an environment of severe economic inequalities, the options for conspicuous
 consumption are in fact further limited to an even smaller part of the
 population.
 On the other hand, a comparison of high quality consumption in the different
 groups of a typical demand survey covers the quality concerns for a larger
 section of the population and views status needs of the consumer as part
 of her long-term utility.
 Even for a study for status consumption alone, the extension of the sense
 of status-consumption to all commodity groups and all consumers would be
 necessary to understand the underlying factors that contribute to status
 in the developing world.
 In Tanzania for example - which we explore in the study - one may be tempted
 to argue - based on the literature on conspicuous consumption - that buying
 clothes indicates higher status.
 But without observing the effect that getting electricity in the house
 or moving to a bigger house may have on a consumer's status, we cannot
 accurately explain the household consumption on status - since the possibility
 that those spending on electricity or housing may actually be cutting down
 on clothing expenditure while deriving status from electricity or house
 ownership cannot be ruled out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard diary and recall methods in a typical survey measure neither
 the quality of consumption nor the socio-economic standing of the consumer
 - the measurement of both of which is central to our goals in the study.
 The measurement of quality is relatively easy - as we rely on the availability
 of price information to classify high-quality (expensive) items apart from
 their cheaper substitutes.
 In the Tanzanian LSMS data therefore, eggs and milk are deemed of lower
 quality than goat and beef for proteins.
 For transport, similarly gasoline-for-car is deemed of lower quality than
 public transport an so on.
 Except for some items that would be missing in the developing country when
 comparing the consumption between two countries, this is a relatively easy
 task.
 For measuring the socio-economic standing of a consumer
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The terms social capital or status capital are also used in the literature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, we rely on the measure of socio-economic-status (SES) - which is a standard
 measure of the socio-economic status often used in the sociological and
 health studies.
 The long-term utility of the consumer in the model thus consists of a vector
 of income, education and region/locality/neighborhood.
 In addition, we also include the ownership of durable goods (defined as
 items to be purchased with an intent of long-term ownership) and a history
 of ENDC in the measures for status.
 This is of key importance since income, education, occupation or residence
 are usually fixed in the short-run.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The accumulation of durable goods serves as one of the indicators of stability
 of high income - as we expect individuals to purchase these durable goods
 (more expensive than quality consumption) only if their expectation of
 stability of income is high (higher than it is compared to when they engage
 in higher quality non-durable consumption).
 To compare the accumulation of long-term durable goods (LTDG) in a developed
 and a developing economy, we order the LTDG in the market based on their
 cost of acquisition.
 The differences in the costs of the two successive assets in this cost-order
 for LTDG present the substitutability between asset acquisition and quality
 consumption.
 A higher difference between two successive LTDG costs would make the consumptio
n of quality more tempting for a consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the developing world, not only are the markets underdeveloped for making
 rental options available for the the expensive durable goods (LTDG), there
 is somewhat of an absence of credit facilities - both of which make the
 difference between successive LTDG costs higher than in the developed countries
 (where markets are more developed and either credit to purchase LTDG or
 direct rental of LTDG is made available to consumer).
 To explain the effect of economic inequality on quality consumption in
 the developing vs the developed countries, we can thus compare the expensive
 non-durable consumption along with the differences between the current
 and next point of LTDG acquisition in the cost curve of LTDG for any two
 selected countries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
LITERATURE SURVEY
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to test - even with a simple model for quality and possession
 of assets - whether prolonged measures of income equality (and therefore
 stagnant ownership of durable goods) can influence non-durable consumption
 asymmetrically when there is a sudden rise in incomes (a problem that may
 be relevant for countries in Africa).
 In a study of conspicuous consumption, Friehe et al 
