\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 consumption in the regions of erstwhile East and West Germany and study
 the effects of the respective stagnant and well-performing states of their
 past economies on status consumption in the unified economy.
 If macroeconomic factors and issues of supply (e.g.
 income inequalities, distribution of resources etc.) can be controlled for
 in the economies, then a model for long-term needs can explain the demand
 pressures induced by economic inequalities across the different economies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lack of data on quality in most consumer surveys however often results
 in the selection of models where a rational consumer - knowing all about
 her future plans - is in fact not expected to engage in any long-term status
 related consumption at all.
 As Thaler et al had argued in their influential paper on a behavioural
 life-cycle hypothesis, there should be no overeating and overspending if
 the consumers were rational (see Shefrin-Thaler 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ShefrinThaler1988"

\end_inset

).
 If there is indeed nothing to be gained by status-related consumption (i.e.
 conspicuous consumption is essentially futile - as argued by Veblen), then
 there is no way for the rational consumer to derive any utility from status-rel
ated consumption.
 However, the mere existence of conspicuous consumption proves that there
 is some utility to be derived by spending on status or quality.
 
\end_layout

