 The futility assumption makes less sense in the developing world 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"

\end_inset

 where there are far fewer exclusive conspicuous items and the expenditure
 on conspicuous items is limited to a much smaller portion of the population.
 The empirical classification of status-items in the developed world itself
 based on visibility is also fraught with problems (escaped only through
 a consumer survey of one's own) - as an item both provides advantages through
 visibility and through quality.
 Instead of deciding on a crisp boundary between visible and non-visible
 utilities, we focus on the quality defined as expensive non-durable consumption
 (which prices status or visible benefits and signals elitism) and ownership
