 a consumer may consider quality for transport more important than quality
 in food (or vice versa).
 However, such an order in the model matters amidst two items only if they
 are in different commodity groups.
 For the items within the group, such a preference doesn't exist in the
 model.
 For example, in the Tanzanian LSMS data where we identify six categories
 - Food, Energy, Transport, Personal Care, Social Functions and Housing/Land,
 visibility may not have much of a role to play within each of the commodity
 groups even though the consumers may consider the quality in one group
 more important than in the other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, the model of the status-cognisant long-term utility considering
 LTDG and ENDC does not view status consumption as futile.
 Instead it relates the quality of non-durable consumption and the ownership
 of long-term durable goods with the perceptions of social mobility.
 Unlike in many studies for status consumption, we assume that the only
